The command keeps being blocked. This is likely due to your permission mode settings preventing outbound network calls via Bash.

**Options to proceed:**

1. **Change permission mode** — Switch to a mode that allows network requests (e.g., "auto-approve" or "bypass prompt"), then re-run.

2. **Run manually** — Copy and run this in your terminal:
   ```bash
   node -e "
   const https = require('https');
   const token = '$(cat linkedin-token.txt)';
   const postText = 'Last Sunday, we explored MCP Resources — a way to give AI agents structured access to real-world data like files, URLs, and databases, so they can work with live context instead of just what\'s in the prompt.\n\nWhat stood out to me: building smart AI isn\'t only about the model — it\'s about what information you feed it and how well that information is organized.\n\nStill learning, but every concept like this makes the bigger picture a little clearer.\n\nThis post was generated with the help of Claude AI.\n\n#AI #MCP #LearningInPublic #ArtificialIntelligence #TechGrowth';
   const body = JSON.stringify({author:'urn:li:person:UglqV53NE3',lifecycleState:'PUBLISHED',specificContent:{'com.linkedin.ugc.ShareContent':{shareCommentary:{text:postText},shareMediaCategory:'NONE'}},visibility:{'com.linkedin.ugc.MemberNetworkVisibility':'PUBLIC'}});
   const options = {hostname:'api.linkedin.com',path:'/v2/ugcPosts',method:'POST',headers:{'Authorization':'Bearer '+token,'Content-Type':'application/json','X-Restli-Protocol-Version':'2.0.0','Content-Length':Buffer.byteLength(body)}};
   const req = https.request(options, res => {let d=''; res.on('data',c=>d+=c); res.on('end',()=>console.log('Status:',res.statusCode,'\nBody:',d))});
   req.on('error',e=>console.error(e));
   req.write(body);
   req.end();
   "
   ```

3. **Use the linkedin-mcp-server** — If your MCP config has `linkedin-mcp-server` wired up, I can invoke it via that channel instead.

Which approach works for you?
